INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Lie on your back; tuck the pelvis so the lower back contacts the floor.
2. Place hands lightly behind the head — do NOT pull on the neck.
3. Brace the abs and curl the chest toward the hips.
4. Squeeze the abs hard at the top, exhale fully.
5. Lower under control — keep tension on the abs the whole way.
6. Breathing: Inhale on the eccentric / lengthening phase. Exhale forcefully as you contract the abs at the top. Empty the lungs at the peak contraction for maximum recruitment.
7. Form check: Tuck the pelvis so the lower back stays in contact with the floor.
8. Form check: Hands light on the head — never pull the neck forward.
9. The Alternating Oblique Sit Ups mainly trains your Obliques (external and internal obliques), Abdominals (rectus abdominis). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'crunch',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=crunch] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.9; McGill, Low Back Disorders 2nd ed. — trunk / core training$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
