SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Mount the bars/bench with arms locked out, shoulders pulled down.
2. Lean slightly forward for chest dips, stay vertical for triceps.
3. Lower until your shoulders are just below the elbows.
4. Drive back up by pushing through the palms — lock out at the top.
5. Avoid swinging; let the chest/triceps do the work.
6. Breathing: Inhale during the eccentric (easier) half of the rep. Exhale during the concentric (harder) half — pushing, pulling, or lifting. Never hold your breath for multiple reps in a row.
7. Form check: Shoulders pulled down and back at the top — never shrug into the bars.
8. Form check: Lower until shoulders are JUST below the elbows; no further.
9. The Bench Triceps Dip Straight Legs mainly trains your Triceps (triceps brachii). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'dip',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=dip] NSCA ESSC 4th ed. ch.13; NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.13 — horizontal pressing$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
FROM public.exercise_library WHERE id = '51d71c18-8fc8-4308-acee-f783e9fa3362'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.exercise_instruction_backup
                  WHERE id = '51d71c18-8fc8-4308-acee-f783e9fa3362');
UPDATE public.exercise_library SET instructions = $instr$1. Mount the bars/bench with arms locked out, shoulders pulled down.
2. Lean slightly forward for chest dips, stay vertical for triceps.
3. Lower until your shoulders are just below the elbows.
4. Drive back up by pushing through the palms — lock out at the top.
5. Avoid swinging; let the chest/triceps do the work.
6. Breathing: Inhale during the eccentric (easier) half of the rep. Exhale during the concentric (harder) half — pushing, pulling, or lifting. Never hold your breath for multiple reps in a row.
7. Form check: Shoulders pulled down and back at the top — never shrug into the bars.
8. Form check: Lower until shoulders are JUST below the elbows; no further.
9. The Bench Triceps Dip Straight Legs mainly trains your Triceps (triceps brachii). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$ WHERE id = '51d71c18-8fc8-4308-acee-f783e9fa3362';

