   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, toes slightly pointed out.
2. Hold your arms out in front for balance (or hands behind your head).
3. Brace your core and look straight ahead.
4. Push your hips back and bend your knees to descend.
5. Drive through your heels to stand back up.
6. Breathing: Inhale through the descent — fill the belly, not the chest. Exhale on the drive up. Keep the breath natural — no forced Valsalva needed without a load.
7. Form check: Weight in the heels and mid-foot.
8. Form check: Go as deep as your mobility allows with good form.
9. The Bodyweight Squats mainly trains your Quadriceps (Quadriceps Femoris), Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'bodyweight_squat',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=bodyweight_squat] NSCA Essentials of Strength Training & Conditioning 4th ed. (Haff & Triplett 2016) ch.13 — squat technique$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
