INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Lie on your side, forearm on the floor, elbow under the shoulder.
2. Stack the feet (or stagger for balance).
3. Lift the hips so the body is one straight line from feet to head.
4. Brace the obliques — no hip sag, no rotation.
5. Hold for the prescribed time, then switch sides.
6. Breathing: Breathe steadily — short, shallow breaths are fine. Do not hold your breath; that spikes blood pressure and shortens the hold. Exhale a touch more forcefully on each breath to keep the core braced.
7. Form check: Squeeze glutes; tuck the pelvis — no sag, no pike.
8. Form check: Press the floor away — pack the shoulders.
9. The Dumbbell Elbow Side Plank mainly trains your Core (Rectus Abdominis, Transverse Abdominis). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'side_plank',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=side_plank] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.9; McGill, Low Back Disorders 2nd ed. — trunk / core training$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
