UPDATE public.exercise_library SET instructions = $instr$1. Sit with your upper back against a bench, bar across your hips (use a pad).
2. Plant feet hip-to-shoulder width, knees ~90° at the top.
3. Tuck the chin, brace the core, and drive through your heels.
4. Lock out with hips fully extended — squeeze the glutes hard.
5. Lower with control to just above the floor, then repeat.
6. Breathing: Inhale at the bottom — pelvis tucked, ribs down. Exhale as you drive the hips up and squeeze the glutes. Inhale at the top before lowering with control.
7. Form check: Tuck the chin and the pelvis — ribs down, not flared.
8. Form check: Drive through the heels, not the toes.
9. The Dumbbell Single-Leg Hip Thrust mainly trains your Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$ WHERE id = 'aecee3b1-d354-4914-bca9-c5f9c56ecf5d';

INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Stand on one leg with a soft knee bend, weight in front of the working hip.
2. Hinge at the working hip, letting the back leg rise behind you.
3. Keep the back flat — chest, hip, and back leg form one straight line.
4. Lower the weight to mid-shin, then return by squeezing the working glute.
5. Reset on the floor between reps if balance is unstable.
6. Breathing: Take a big breath into your belly at the top before setting up. Hold the brace throughout the pull — do not exhale mid-rep. Exhale at lockout, reset the breath before the next rep.
7. Form check: Never round the lower back.
8. Form check: Keep the bar close to the body throughout.
9. The Dumbbell Single-Leg Single-Arm Deadlift mainly trains your Hamstrings (Biceps Femoris, Semitendinosus), Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'single_leg_deadlift',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=single_leg_deadlift] NSCA ESSC 4th ed. ch.13; McGill, Low Back Disorders 2nd ed. — neutral-spine hip hinge$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
