INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Stand on one foot with the other leg extended out in front of you.
2. Hold your arms forward as a counterbalance.
3. Push your hips back and lower with the working leg only.
4. Keep the working knee tracking over the toes — heel stays planted.
5. Drive up through the heel back to standing, then switch sides.
6. Breathing: Inhale through the descent — fill the belly, not the chest. Exhale on the drive up. Keep the breath natural — no forced Valsalva needed without a load.
7. Form check: Plant the working heel — never let it lift.
8. Form check: Counterbalance with the arms forward to stay upright.
9. The Dumbbell Single-Leg Squat With Support (Pistol) mainly trains your Quadriceps (Quadriceps Femoris). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'pistol_squat',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=pistol_squat] NSCA Essentials of Strength Training & Conditioning 4th ed. (Haff & Triplett 2016) ch.13 — squat technique$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
