                  WHERE id = '7cecfd18-845a-4276-82aa-66b19ddf4dd1');
UPDATE public.exercise_library SET instructions = $instr$1. Move into the position slowly — stop at the first point of mild tension.
2. Hold without bouncing; static stretches respond to time, not force.
3. Breathe into the stretch — inhale deeply, exhale and ease a touch deeper.
4. Aim for 30–60 seconds per side; never push into sharp pain.
5. Come out as deliberately as you went in.
6. Breathing: Inhale deeply through the nose into the belly. Exhale slowly through the mouth and ease a fraction deeper into the stretch. Never hold your breath — breathing is what allows tissue to release.
7. Form check: Move slowly into the position; never bounce.
8. Form check: Breathe deeply — exhalations let the tissue lengthen.
9. The Monkey Pose mainly trains your Hamstrings (Biceps Femoris, Semitendinosus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$ WHERE id = '7cecfd18-845a-4276-82aa-66b19ddf4dd1';

INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Set up in a high plank — wrists under shoulders, glutes tight.
2. Drive one knee toward the chest without letting the hips rise.
3. Quickly switch legs as if running in plank position.
4. Keep the upper body rock-solid; the legs do the work.
5. Set a steady cadence — speed is the last priority.
6. Breathing: Settle into a steady breath rhythm — 1 in / 1 out per movement. Do not hold your breath; intensity is high enough that breath holding will gas you out. If breath outpaces rhythm, slow the work to match the breath.
7. Form check: Wrists stay under the shoulders — do not creep forward.
8. Form check: Hips stay LOW — no piking.
9. The Mountain Climber Jump mainly trains your Quadriceps (Quadriceps Femoris), Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'mountain_climber',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=mountain_climber] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.9; McGill, Low Back Disorders 2nd ed. — trunk / core training$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
