INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Hold a kettlebell or dumbbell at chest level — elbows tucked under.
2. Stand with feet shoulder-width, toes slightly out.
3. Brace and descend between your knees with an upright torso.
4. Drop until your elbows graze the inside of your knees.
5. Drive through your heels back to standing, ribs over hips.
6. Breathing: Take a big belly-breath before you descend and brace your core. Hold the brace through the bottom of the rep. Exhale forcefully on the drive up.
7. Form check: Weight in your heels and mid-foot.
8. Form check: Go as deep as your mobility allows with good form.
9. The Narrow Stance Heels Elevated Dumbbell Goblet Squats mainly trains your Quadriceps (Quadriceps Femoris), Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'goblet_squat',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=goblet_squat] NSCA Essentials of Strength Training & Conditioning 4th ed. (Haff & Triplett 2016) ch.13 — squat technique$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
