   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Stand tall, bar at hip height, feet hip-width.
2. Maintain a slight, fixed knee bend — do not turn this into a squat.
3. Hinge at the hips, pushing them BACK as the bar slides down the thighs.
4. Stop just below the knee or where your hamstring stretch peaks.
5. Drive hips forward to stand — finish with glutes squeezed, not lower-back arched.
6. Breathing: Take a big breath into your belly at the top before setting up. Hold the brace throughout the pull — do not exhale mid-rep. Exhale at lockout, reset the breath before the next rep.
7. Form check: Hips back, NOT a squat — knee bend stays fixed.
8. Form check: Bar slides down the thighs; never drift away from the body.
9. The Romanian Deadlift Barbell mainly trains your Back (Erector Spinae), Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'rdl',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=rdl] NSCA ESSC 4th ed. ch.13; McGill, Low Back Disorders 2nd ed. — neutral-spine hip hinge$instr$, '2084-2026-05-18'
